{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650839"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:17:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18420"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18420"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.62,0.19,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11138"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79448"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11138"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79448"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the ultimate cause of death in many cases of cancer cachexia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weakness leading to a fatal fall","Loss of respiratory muscle function","Failure of cardiac muscle","Loss of liver function","Collapse of skeleton"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECancer cachexia is a multifactorial syndrome characterised by severe body weight, fat, and muscle loss, and it is often associated with advanced cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure of cardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E causing cardiovascular complications is one of the major causes of death in cancer patients with cachexia. Patients present similarly to chronic heart failure with fatigue, shortness of breath, and impaired exercise tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of respiratory muscle function\u003C/strong\u003E leads to respiratory failure, as the weakened muscles are unable to support adequate ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeakness leading to a fatal fall\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential risk in cachectic patients due to muscle wasting, but it is not the primary cause of death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of liver function\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically the direct cause of death in cancer cachexia, although liver function can be compromised in advanced cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollapse of skeleton\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct cause of death in cancer cachexia, although bone health can be affected by the overall nutritional and metabolic state.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cancer cachexia is a complex syndrome characterised by severe body weight, fat, and muscle loss and is often associated with cancer.","The ultimate cause of death in cancer cachexia is often due to cardiac failure.","Management of cancer cachexia focuses on nutritional support and addressing the underlying cancer."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Esper DH, Harb WA. The cancer cachexia syndrome: a review of metabolic and clinical manifestations. Nutr Clin Pract. 2005 Aug;20(4):369-76. doi: 10.1177/0115426505020004369. PMID: 16207677.","Mariean CR, Tiuc\u0103 OM, Mariean A, Cotoi OS. Cancer Cachexia: New Insights and Future Directions. Cancers (Basel). 2023 Nov 26;15(23):5590. doi: 10.3390/cancers15235590. PMID: 38067294; PMCID: PMC10705516.","Rausch V, Sala V, Penna F, Porporato PE, Ghigo A. Understanding the common mechanisms of heart and skeletal muscle wasting in cancer cachexia. Oncogenesis. 2021 Jan;10(1)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18420"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T19:01:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T19:01:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11138"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na